Ebinuma demonstrated the use of GPS for rendezvous. He developed an extended Kalman ﬁlter to perform real-time relative navigation and used a hardware-in-the-loop test facility, which integrates navigation and guidance for rendezvous. However, his models assumed that GPS was always available and did not include multipath or blockage of the GPS signals.5
The most recent research on navigation during proximity operations conducted by Um examined spacecraft relative navigation using an integrated GPS/INS in the vicinity of the ISS.6 The GPS/INS was a loosely coupled system, which included two Kalman ﬁlters, one to process the GPS measurements and the other to combine the INS measurements with the output of the GPS ﬁlter. The INS part of the system was simulated in software and the GPS measurements were collected from a Mitel Architect GPS receiver being stimulated by a GSSI STR4760 GPS simulator.
The major contributions of this paper include:
1. A spacecraft INS error model is developed. Most INS error models are designed for terrestrial navigation and therefore are formulated in an earthﬁxed reference frame. The error model developed in this paper is formulated in an inertial reference frame, which is more useful for spacecraft in orbit.
2. A GPS error model which includes the eﬀects of GPS signal blockage and multipath caused by the ISS.
3. A proposed GPS/INS Kalman ﬁlter design for an orbiting spacecraft and a simulation of the navigation performance during a rendezvous with the ISS.
INS Error Model
In order to design an integrated GPS/INS navigation system for spacecraft, a linear INS error model has been developed. The INS system-level error model describes the errors in position, velocity and attitude due to various error sources. In most cases, these models are formulated in terms of latitude, longitude and altitude errors and east, north and vertical velocity errors. Attitude errors have been expressed in terms of rotation matrices, tilt angles or quaternions.
In the case of a spacecraft in orbit, it is convenient to formulate the INS system-level error model in an inertial reference frame as Friedland did in 1978.7 Friedland’s formulation is used in this paper. A similar model was developed and used by Crain and Bishop for analyzing Mars entry navigation.8
The sensor-level models describe the errors in speciﬁc force measurements taken by accelerometers and errors in angular rate measurements taken by gyroscopes. The sensor error models used by most authors have the same form but sometimes diﬀer in the

stochastic processes (random walk or Gauss-Markov processes) used to model various component errors such as accelerometer bias or gyro drift. These differences are due to the nature of the instrument or the data available on the instrument. Detailed data on a particular sensor are often not available so a simpler model must be used.
